76561198042646749,Recommended,249230,24256833,"Posted: 11 July, 2016",all,kris.aalst,"Risen 3 is a third person open world action roleplaying game made by Piranha Bytes, the team that gave us the Gothic games and of course the first two Risen games. It's hard to talk about Risen 3 without referring to the previous games, which I'll call 'PB games' for short.To summarize:Risen 3 is definitely a step up from Risen 2 but all in all, it is probably still a game that only fans of PB games will love and a game that only fans of the genre may learn to like.To talk about this game more in-depth, I'll take the list I used for my reviews of 'Risen' and 'Risen 2'.Melee combatThe melee combat in Risen 2 was bad, very bad. The melee combat in Risen 3 is a lot better. It would certainly not win any prizes for the most exciting combat in a RPG ever, but after the fiasco of Risen 2 it feels like a huge improvement. The melee combat in Risen 3 is a lot like it was in the first Witcher game. Your character can perform a combo of moves and all you need to do is click the mouse at the right time to make sure the combo is performed correctly. If you click at the wrong time, the combo will be interrupted by the opponent or you will at least notice a decrease in your effectiveness (lower attack speed and damage dealt).The secondary weapons are back: you can use a pistol, a crossbow or throwing daggers. But since melee combat relies on performing a series of successive attacks (combo), you will hardly ever use a secondary weapon because that interrupts the combo flow.Ranged combatThe ranged combat in Risen 3 is about the same as it was in Risen 2. Muskets and shotguns are back, they work about the same as in Risen 2 and they are about as powerful as they were in Risen 2. But because of the improved melee combat and the return of magic, ranged combat isn't the only viable build anymore like it was in Risen 2.MagicMagic is back after being pretty much absent in Risen 2. Each of the three factions have their own type of magic (rune magic, crystal magic or voodoo magic). I can't really comment further on how a mage build would function in Risen 3 as I went with melee/ranged.Learning curve for your characterLike in all PB games, there isn't just a learning curve for the player but for the character, too. He needs to learn to fight better. As the game progresses and you improve your character's skills, you actually feel your character getting better. This curve is not very steep in Risen 3, making it by far the easiest PB game so far. For the sake of Steam Achievements, I only improved my stats and skills a bit and then started saving 'glory points' (what XP is called in this game) to be able to max out each stat one by one (there is an achievement for getting each stat to 100). This means that I went through the better part of the game with only minimal stats and skills, and the game still felt too easy. You can up the difficulty in the game settings, but that only makes the monsters hit harder, which isn't really an issue when the problem is that most monsters don't hit you at all. You could artificially increase the difficulty in two ways, though:go solo, so don't take an npc companion with you: I should have done this earlier but the first few hours you need a companion so you get used to it. Also, there are companions that are part of the factions that live on the main islands and they have a personal quest there, so you miss out on some stuff if you go solo. But it was only after I started to go questing without a companion that I felt challenged in this game.don't use dodge: dodging is overpowered. It has no cooldown and opponents can't interrupt your dodging, so you're actually invincible while dodging. Combined with a companion who will take aggro while you're dodging, this can make the game way too easy.FactionsFactions are back, after being more or less absent in Risen 2. They aren't as different or game defining as they were in the Gothic games, but at least they feel like real factions and they come with their own armor sets, like in the good old days ;-)TrainersThe character development system is very close to the one Risen 2 had, with some minor but welcome changes. You still increase stats with 'glory' (XP) and you still learn or increase skills by finding and paying a trainer who can teach you. It would go too far to describe all the skills and all the stats and their impact on the skills in this review, but I must say that I found the overall character development system in Risen 3 a bit better than in Risen 2.Great atmosphereThe settings, the NPCs, the towns, the music, the humour, ... everything adds to a distinct atmosphere that only PB can create. Although the 'slightly dumbing down' of Risen 2 & 3 compared to earlier PB games is still noticeable, there is a slight improvement compared to Risen 2. NPCs will react to your actions (e.g. stealing in plain sight) a bit more often and a bit more logically than they did in Risen 2, but it's still far from the first four PB games.Something that reminds me of Gothic 2, is that a part of the world of Risen 3 is 'recycled content' from the previous game. Some people find this incredibly lazy. While I see their point, I personally like the vaguely familiar settings. Those islands look different enough from the previous game to be a largely new experience, but you have a feeling of “Hey, here used to be...” and a curiosity of “I wonder if ... is still there”.There are a ton of references to the Gothic games in Risen 3. For starters, some creatures from the Gothic series are back: scavengers, swamp golems, snappers and dragon snappers. There are also a few encounters and easter eggs referring to earlier PB games. For example,you'll come across an annoying fellow called Mud who follows you around and won't shut up (same as in Gothic 1), you'll meet the nameless hero you played in the first two Risen games and you'll see a lot of dead people again like Steelbeard and inquisitor Mendoza.Some notes about the Steam AchievementsThe achievements aren't bugged like they were for Risen 2. If you want to get all the achievements, you will either need three playthroughs or plan a bit. That means:join each faction (save, join, reload) before joining one for good.if you aren't going to join the Demonhunters faction for good: when you join them briefly to get the achievement for that, also do the quest 'A new rank' for Drake before reloading. This quest is Demonhunters only and as a part of that quest, you need to complete another quest called 'Zak's temptation' on Antigua, which has an achievement of its own.gather enough glory points to max your lowest stat and then max each stat one by one (save, max a stat, reload, max next stat, reload, etc.) before allocating your glory points where you want them for your build.start playing the game as a good guy to get the achievement for getting your soul rating over 90 (I'd save at 80 or so, then give all soul dust to Edward to get soul rating above 90, then reload), then start playing as a complete prick to get soul below 10 for another achievement."
76561198017425718,Recommended,249230,11685536,"Posted: 13 August, 2014",all,Sluggeto,"First I'd like to say I went through many of the reviews here, many of the thumbs down played less than 2 hours, came here and passed judgement... an open world RPG with hundreds of quests and destinations, too many NPC's to name and a host of new features, yet 1.7 hours and it sucks. Really.Okay, that said, here's my quick opinion, if you played Gothic 2 there is much to enjoy here, the game is similar in many ways, but perhaps too easy to start. If you are looking for Witcher 3 graphics, nope, want Halo shooter action, nope, this game is exactly what it tries to be, a game for those who enjoyed the Gothic & Risen game world and wants more.If you are looking try this game keep in mind, those who play 1.5 hours after spenting 50 bucks, then come here to condemn it, you might want to consider the ability of anyone to jugde this type of game after such a short time, I suspect they were not aware of the history that comes with this game."
