,Recommended,249230,30297510,Posted: 3 March,all,Gestalt,"To start with, I finished ""Risen 3"" 5 days ago. So with its completion, I have done with the series, at least for now. I think I can say without hesitation that Piranha Bytes did a marvelous job there with Risen series.In regards to Risen 3, I have read a lot of reviews and comments that says the game is just more of the same of its predecessors and I kinda agree on that. However, I think it is a good thing that R3 got the best of these two worlds.As an RPG gamer, what impressed me in R1, is the faction system which utterly failed in R2 because your faction was shaping your play style and it was limiting the player to a certain role. Now these factions in R2 plays a role in R3 but for instance, if you want to be an inquisitor, now you can't but there is a whole bunch of quest for them, too and even if you are submitted to another faction which also can heavily consists of magic usage, you can develop you character in both magic skills and/or other gun/musket skills.  Also faction system makes replayability of the game skyrocket, just like it did in R1 and R2; you can revisit the game and play a different storyline with a different faction.Story-wise, it is on par with 2 previous games; although, for me, first one is still the best. It goes without saying, it was also heart-warming to see the characters from previous games; heck, you can even meet with the antagonist of the second game(playerchar) and clink some booze with him; even though it plays a small role it is very nice addition and I really appreciate the developers for giving us, players, tangible lines to merge previous games to the newest and latest title.As for the map, it shares the same location with 2nd game's. I am not sure but maybe, 1 or 2 island were added. So if you played the 2nd game, it's not a big surprise to say  yourself ""I think I know this place but from where?"". One can say it is a disadvantage or a proof that developers didn't work as hard as they worked for the 2nd game but I found it really satisfying. Because instead of spending time on recreating a new world, they spend the time on enriching the story and quests, giving us a better game in terms of story content from the other previous titles. The story length is quite satisfying in comparison to today's standard; just to give an example, my play-through took around 45 hours.So what I don't like about R3 is, still the same since the beginning of these series. Item-wise, you are still searching for the strongest weapon in regards to your level, not really thinking of any other option because there is no real option there. Second, Lockpicking and Persuasion skills are all needed but for one tenth of whole cases, really. In nine tenth of cases treasure loots or things we steal are totally garbage.So there is not much negativity for me in this game; even they integrate a teleporter system. In the previous titles, it was becoming tiresome to walk over all the island just for 1 quest item.So I think I can safely recommend Risen 3 to rpg lovers and also, with its friendly UI, even to the newcomers from other genres."
