76561198088884238,Not Recommended,249230,11906443,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,alex.link501,"I think that the decision whether or not to recommend this game was quite a close one for me because while the game does have allot going against it on paper it was still fun to play I just think that it got held back because unfortunately no one area of the game stood out as having been particularly well executed throughout.On the one hand the levels are quite well done and there is allot to do in the game, plus you have a wide variety of choices when deciding on how to build your character so you don’t have to decide what play style you want to employ up front. There are also a wide variety of side quests to pursue which provide quite a few hours of entertainment. The crew of your ship which you will build up over time are interesting as they will make comments as you travel with them, some of which are fairly amusing. Another thing that I liked was the skill system, to many games have long complex skill trees that don’t feel like they contribute to much more than the player stats. In risen 3 you can learn any skill you want and allot of the spells are interesting to play with, from being able to blink around the field to turning yourself into a parrot to more aggressive combat spells there is allot to play and experiment with. While I know that some people have had stability issues I’ve yet to crash once and fps drops are small and few so I personally think that the game is fairly stable.On the other hand this game does disappoint particularly as you progress, this is due to your character becoming overpowered and there being no real counter balance making combat a chore as the enemies don’t become notably stronger or varied also meaning that there is little incentive to mix things up. Another damming issue is that you don’t have to get too far into the game to have seen every enemy except the bosses. Graphics were another issue, while the environment may be appealing the rest is fairly sub-standard and broken graphics and clipping are a common issue. It’s also fairly easy to glitch a quest with issues ranging from broken markers through to the quest being impossible to finish effectively breaking the game forcing you to either load an earlier save or start a new game. while the game does have some replay value from joining different factions and completing different quests it could do with some incentive to start a new game such as unlocking (significantly) harder difficulties or additional content. I think that the straw that broke the horses back though was the highly anti-climactic endgame. The last few quests and the final cut scene were extremely disappointing because allot of what you had done to that point seemed to fizzle out leaving you asking the question “what, is that it! What the (inset preferred term to express outrage)!”pros:.interesting environment.the story was great up until the last chapter.fully voiced (though it’s kind of expected in this sort of game these days).interesting characters not the best ever but still ok.stablecons:.not challenging after a point + various balancing issues.anti-climactic ending and no closer.can bug out on you either quest markers or in a breaking way.poor graphicsIn conclusion I felt that while the game was fun to play it doesn’t feel finished and while I can accept that not all games are going to be polished to a mirror shine they need to pick up the slack in some regard whether that be through the story or the gameplay mechanics and risen 3 ultimately just didn’t do that."
