76561198143126692,Not Recommended,249230,11733437,"Posted: 15 August, 2014",all,valevergonzo,"Firstly, although my game time says 4 hours, my save file says 6. 6 hours of gameplay might not be enough to properly review this game, it seems to be improving, but is all the time I am willing spend here for now. I bought this game based on the various reviews here swearing that the game will get better, but honestly, who wants to go through 5 or 6 hours of gameplay before having fun?The combat is clunky. The attacks are not responsive, the characters go through pirouettes, leaps and lunges to deliver a single blow. At the beginning of the game the delay between the strikes in your 3-hit combo are long enough to allow the enemy to interrupt you every single time. You will be reduced to using the same hit and roll tactic for next 3 hours, whittling away at the enemy's health while your companion does most of the heavy lifting... Unless the companion AI suddenly decides to stop attacking or has gotten stuck somewhere, in that case whittle away.On the other hand, as you progress you acquire new types of weapons and skills that really add up to the combat. It can still be frustrating, but after 5 hours or so (your mileage might vary depending on the places you visit first and how you develop your character) you start to see where the combat is trying to go. I do not if it eventually gets there, I will update this review when I revisit the game.This might be surprising, but the combat isn't what finally pushed me away from the game. It is the conversation that did it for me, and that is quite sad because they went through the effort of voicing pretty much everything. The problem is that the conversations meander so much, there are so many exchanges in one conversation branch that hold no value, they don't develop the characters, they don't introduce lore, nor do they mimic normal conversation. It is really, baffling how much extra effort went where it needed to.I understand that a complaint for the previous game was the lack of voiced acting or how little voice acting there was, I am not too sure about this, but regardless, there is just too much useless and pointless dialogue in this game, but I might have been able to take if it wasn't for the horrible voice acting.  That's right, there is awkward writing being voiced very badly. This is the first time that this has affected my gameplay so much that I have stopped playing.All that said, the game has the potential to improve plenty, perhaps by the 15th hour everything else would be sufficiently enjoyable that you can look past the scrip and voice acting, but if that is the case, it would be better to wait for this game to go on sale, currently it isn't worth the asking price."
,Not Recommended,249230,29126096,Posted: 8 January,all,Skeletor,"I really, REALLY wanted to like this game. Hell, it was a new Piranha Bytes release, and I LOVE these devs. However, I'm not sure what's going on with them after seeing this. Sadly, I would have taken more consideration into pre-ordering it had I known what Risen 2 ended up being, as PB in my opinion has had a relatively solid track record with their games, with titles that were at least good enough for me to pitch in and support them, and that's saying something in most cases.I've been a Piranha Bytes fan to the core when it comes to their RPGs since I had the manual dexterity to use a keyboard, and Gothic was actually my first RPG experience. Even to this day, I have a hard time finding games in the RPG sector that manage to captivate me as much as G1 and G2 did.However, this isn't a Gothic 1 or Gothic 2 review. This is a Risen 3 review, so let's get on with it.What really ruined it for me:The Combat-   -   -   -   -   -This was the first thing I noticed when I began playing the game, and I have to say PB fell flat on their face with this one. First and foremost, the main character has about as much ability in using a sword as a dead cat, and he's about as stalwart as one, too. His attacks have an atrocious wind up that make even the simplest combat situations into an ordeal of timing and hoping the enemies don't hit you first, which brings me to my next subject: Enemies have NO WIND UP to balance this out. Just about everything you encounter and fight in the game will attack you relentlessly and without any kind of delay, meaning that if you go in and swing at the enemy, they can just attack and interrupt you, doing damage and bringing you back to square one. Oh, and that's another thing. EVERYTHING, and I mean EVERYTHING stuns your character. Tiny♥♥♥♥♥beach insect thing? (I still have yet to understand those creatures.) Yeah, their tiny attack will stagger your character the same way you'd expect him to if he got clocked upside the head by Chuck Liddell.As a whole, this results in an absolutely infuriating combat experience that was one of the main reasons I had to put the game down for good. It's completely unbearable, and frankly I've come to expect far more from these developers.Now, I know, I've seen it everywhere. People could say that Gothic's combat was just as awful, if not worse, but there's a key difference there: Gothic's combat is anything but horrible, for one. If anything, it's about all you should expect from an RPG from around the year 2000; on the other hand, this game from 2015 manages to have combat that, unlike Gothic, doesn't just take a bit of time to get a hang of, but instead is completely impossible to work with and that, in my opinion, makes the experience null and void. I even used cheats to increase my combat skill in hopes of making my character's attacks worthwhile, and even THIS did absolutely nothing whatsoever.In terms of major flaws, this really is the only one, and it manages to be so outstandingly, so GLORIOUSLY bad that the game is completely ruined by it.Now, the game has some things that I like about it, namely the fact that it really does feel like a Piranha Bytes game still. The dialogue, characters, world, and music all still make me feel like I'm playing a good old PB game, but once I get into a fight I simply can't force myself to get through the whole thing.Now, for an open recommendation for the developers and a closing statement:You clever ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s have given me gaming experiences throughout my entire life, and I absolutely adore you all for it. I've often burst out in laughter from the Hero's dialogue options and an NPC's response, as well as the numerous easter eggs and goodies you leave lying around. This, just as often as I've have slammed my fist down on my desk in frustration from the challenging and punishing, yet rewarding combat experience, but this game hardly managed to do any of that for me, as the whole thing was sadly cut short by its one fatal flaw.When I say this next bit, I want you guys to know (and this goes to other readers as well) that I'm not just putting on the nostalgia blinders; I just know a working formula when I see it.Hypothetically, if you lot made another RPG, regardless of if it's Risen or something new entirely, and you used the same formula for G1 and G2 (here's where you could call me out on nostalgia blindness, if it weren't for the fact that an overwhelming number of your fans will show agreement) and adapted it for a modern market, using a newer engine with better graphics and the like, it would probably end up being another great installment; and, when I say 'formula' I'm talking about everything that made the first two Gothic games what they were, from the controls to the stats. Hell, you could make it on the old G2 engine and it'd probably still be great, but if there's one thing I'll admit, it's that the controls, while not inherently bad and not in need of outright change, could definitely use a tune up to make it feel a bit more fluid and responsive.At this point, I doubt anything in the paragraph above will happen, but I do sincerely believe it'd do the team a lot better than what they're going with as of now. Some things don't need to change, and it really does seem like the games started going downhill once the controls went through the big overhaul they did starting with Gothic 3, which changed the other two games' main control drawback of being somewhat stiff at times and generally feeling rather old-school to making the whole thing just feel outright clumsy. Risen 3 seems to have marked the apex of this clumsiness, and it's so atrocious that I couldn't even recommend this to my worst enemy.Hopefully this review shed some light for players on the fence about getting it and why I sincerely believe they should just go to GOG and buy one of the Gothic games instead. (It's probably obvious which two I recommend.) If you can be a proper human and adapt to the controls that are most definitely different from what most are accustomend to, you'll find what is an experience that is worlds better than what this title provides, and possibly one that you may find unforgettable."
,Recommended,249230,12690087,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,decivodennio,"beautiful. just finished what i'm hoping is not the last pirahna bytes game. and even though i don't really write reviews and am new to steam i figured the newest edition to my favorite series deserves a shout out. i discovered risen 1 a couple years ago in a bargain bin and didnt expect much... just a no name company with what looked like a simplistic, guided rpg.... i was surprised at the little details put into it that i had never seen before and a friend told me about gothic.  my next was gothic 3 which to this day is my favorite game right up there with skyrim, fallout 3, kotor.their games seem to get a lot of flack, and i think that is mostly for the combat system... which i always thought was fine. no this isn't a world where you start off hacking through hoards of enemies seamlessly, if you want an action game... get an action game.if you want a role-playing experience where you are put into the shoes of a character and asked to build them and guide them through a process than all of their games are great(though don't get the steam version of gothic 2 one of the steam patches broke it and it stopped booting in the fifth chapter for me..... all my disc versions have been fine though)first off, all their games are 'deceptively' open world. meaning, you look at a mini map( in the later ones) and see roads and mountains and assume you are supposed to take those roads. one of the things i find so wonderful about their games is: yes, they offer a road.... but if you don't follow it they reward you.risen 3 doesn't have the greatest feeling of accomplishment and i think that may be do to making teleporting easier. teleportation stones used to be a big prize and this feels more similar to arcania.... too many stones means you aren't excited about it any more. though that could just be compared to gothic 3 which had the biggest moment of ""score!"" of any game i had ever played with finding all 6 druid stones when people online would all swear their were only 5 and the mentioning of the 6th was a bug. finding something that the internet hadn't found for years... that makes a game stick with you.this one didn't have as many of those moments, unlocking unlimited flying and the 'reach far away objects' hand were my biggest. but it still sticks true to its roots and gives a gaming experience that rewards exploration. and player control of the leveling process.this is easier than it's predecessors, but their games are all designed to be hard at the beginning and easy later on and i think that is brilliant. there is nothing more annoying than leveling up only to have enemies take longer to kill.... ok i don't play games for the repetitious hack and slash. i play for the character development and story... i'm one of those weirdos that reads all the game books and listens to what the characters say. i like games that let you ease in, explore cautiously, and then once you have been everywhere don't make you repeat things.i think the biggest annoyance in the game was the knife mini game, sometimes my knives would be sticking out of the board and i get no points -_- that and the one character that i got, started a quest with... then he leaves.other than those things, risen 3 like its predecessors is a game that gives what it gets. if you run through the trails, don't care about dialogue, and are only there to kill things than you will get a shallow action experience. take that extra time to climb that highest peak, to fly in between shadow minions, to read the items in your inventory. and you find a game that people put effort into. which is more than can be said for most of what comes out today."
