,Recommended,249230,11731473,"Posted: 15 August, 2014",all,Ye sons of shotten herrings!,"(The game took me 35-40 hours to complete, Steam failed to record some of them, so the displayed amount is missing at least 8 hours) If you know Piranha Bytes and their history, you know what you're getting yourself into: A unique and memorable adventure with quirks both major and minor. Virtually everyone would like to see another proper Gothic game, but PB is keeping in mind what the market lacks at any given time and what the publisher may be willing to shell out money for. Back in 2012, it made sense for them to try out a different setting for Risen 2. After all, it had to compete with the likes of Skyrim, and a small studio such as PB has to pick its battles. Risen 2 was a sequel developed from scratch (content-wise) – no easy task, I imagine. They probably could not afford to ditch it all again for Risen 3 and instead opted for a more iterative approach, applying a thin layer of Gothic in the meantime to please the impatient fans. Thus, it feels more like a very large content update to Risen 2 than a true sequel, and PB have not quite delivered on their promise to go back to their roots. I'm not going to talk about story and graphics, as those elements are just solid, do the job and do not stand out to me. What does stand out, is the world.The world:The islands can be visited in any order this time around. They have been lovingly crafted, with many small highlights and cheekily placed treasures waiting to be uncovered. Carefully placed objects tell stories without using words, such as skeletons surrounded by bottles of rum in a secluded spot or a monkey messing around among bananas, voodoo dolls and corpses. There were countless occasions of these enriching little things that never failed to make me smile or ask myself ""WTF happened here?"". The world is teeming with quests (300+ of them) that mostly revolve around fetching and killing stuff. Their presentation through funny and witty dialogue (which does have its cheesy moments) makes them rewarding to complete beyond the glory and loot you get. Swearing is indeed overused, which is a trademark and a welcome recurring theme in the German version, but probably superfluous in the eyes of the English audience. The world and the characters that populate it can suck you in for countless hours at a time. What bothers me is the use of recycled locations from Risen 2 (such as Antigua and Tacarigua), which, apart from the shadow realm's dark taint, retain their Carribean atmosphere.A thin layer of Gothic, weapons & armor:PB promised to go back to their roots and create a darker atmosphere. There were indeed (very short) moments where I felt like I was playing a Gothic game again, largely due to the new locations, factions and their armor sets. Roaming through the swamplands in a demon hunter's armor that looks like a beautiful cross between a dragon hunter's armor (G2) and an Old Camp one (G1) felt great. However, once I returned to my ship and met a parrot named Polly that told me to shave, nostalgia was quickly smothered. There are a few reincarnated minor NPCs from the old games, such as Mud (G1), an annoying, needy motormouth following you around for a bit, and Moe (G2), a violent bully demanding a toll from everyone trying to enter a tavern. Such small instances of fan service kindle hope for a more substantial return to Gothic in the future.Aside from the faction-specific armor sets, there is still a huge emphasis on pirate's clothing. This results in an muddled mixture of epochs and settings in places. Moreover, it's a shame that some stronger versions of armor pieces are just recolorings of the previous ones (e.g. a third-rank demon hunter helmet is a shade lighter than a second-rank one). Re-using assets from within this game and the previous one and applying a different coat of paint to some may be a necessity because of the development team's small size and budget. However, it seriously hurts immersion and they need to apply more polish and care to their equipment in future games.The types of weapons you'll find are again ripped from different eras and settings. There are Gothicesque axes and maces, there is your typical pirate gear and then there are a few questionable design choices. For example, the strongest musket in the game looks like an overdesigned modern-day (scoped...) air rifle that is made of bright, varnished wood. The fact that it says ""way ahead of its time"" in the description doesn't help much. By mixing medieval-looking arms, pirate sabers and fancy guns, PB created a rather incoherent set of tools.Combat:Serviceable, but still rather quirky. You'll find that monsters essentially teleport to your location from 10 meters away and repeatedly knock you back in a straight line. This gives a very rigid and stiff feel to the whole affair when it comes to sword fighting. Thankfully, you can dodge and pick up more moves along the way, but most of the time surviving melee combat felt more like exploitation of design flaws than standing up to a challenge to me. Many have said that it gets better later on as you get stronger and master your timing, but I really wasn't enticed to put up with sword fighting for that long. The fact that they re-introduced offensive magic abilities (painfully absent in Risen 2) adds some much needed flow and diversity. Muskets still provide an easy way to avoid finicky sword fighting and just shoot s#it in the face Indiana Jones style. I would not call them overpowered per say, as they behave and do damage as you'd expect, but still quite out of place in a Piranha Bytes RPG.Conclusion:Piranha Bytes took Risen 2 as a foundation, made it less linear, a little bit better and added a few excellent islands and factions. The result is a fun and engaging, though incoherent pirate game with a hint of Gothic/Risen 1 and plenty of the old PB quirks. That's a little less than I was hoping for, but about what I was expecting. Overall, I'm satisfied with Risen 3 and I can't wait for what future games might have in store."
76561198045224987,Recommended,249230,25226407,"Posted: 29 August, 2016",all,mrwinn,"Was gluded to the game, sometimes with sweating palms, I guess this gives a great review of a Very well written game with many alternatives plus outcomes, can't wait until Risen 4, if it is in progress makes it's way to Steam"
,Recommended,249230,28743919,"Posted: 28 December, 2016",all,Discotech *in korea,"I loved Gothic 2, but never really ventured out to play any other games by PB.I picked this up on a whim, and I'm completely blown away - in a good way.Yes, the dialogue is cheesy. The script can be bad and jump around. The bugs can be awful, and laughable. You may rage the first time you accidentally back up a palm tree during combat only to fall out and die. You'll get headaches from the twitching textures, and the jittery lighting during cutscenes. You'll think the voice actors are sometimes intentionally trying to be do a bad job. The quality of the character design varies greatly from on to another.But, I still love this game, and for a good many reasons.Combat is excellent. It won't be everyones cup of tea, but its a better twist on difficult than some other games. I hate combat and levelling in Skyrim. I love combat and levelling in this game. It just feels better, and I feel like I'm accomplishing something. Enemy placement is also excellent. The world is dangerous. For example, after returning to the tutorial area after finishing the tutorial. I had killed all the monsters, and was grabbing a shroom from near a pool of water and waterfall. I almost jumped out of my seat when a massive crocodile charged at me. Almost died, but surviving a far stronger enemy after being surprised felt great.I really love the level design. Risen 3 takes relatively small maps, and makes the most of them. I love exploring and trying to find every nook and cranny, because you actually benefit from doing it. Think that ledge over there looks like you can land on it? There's probably some dead dude in a weird position, with some coins and a bottle of rum. Maybe some flowers for some extra stat points. Looks like there is an out of the way beach around a jutting out rock? I bet you'll find some useful loot, and some lore. Found a way onto that roof that makes it seem like you were glitching the game? Nope, devs figured players would do that and planted a few potions/spells.The devs understand me as a player. They know I like to mess with things, and they took it in stride and made their game great.This game won't be everyone's cup of tea, but for me it's up there. I give it an 8/10. Well worth the cost, especially on sale."
