76561198154777450,Recommended,249230,30437192,Posted: 10 March,all,gaming2012,"I would definitely recommend this game.The graphics are good, particularly the environment.  There's quite a bit of fun dialog with NPCs and your companions which had me laughing at times, it was entertaining.  There are a lot of side quests which I didn't get to finish all of because I got so focused on completing the main story line.  That's actually a compliment though because I was so focused on the main story because I'd really gotten caught up in it.  Towards the end of the story line I was REALLY wanting to kick the butt of the main bad guy.  In my first play through I focused mainly on melee weapons (swords) and enjoyed the combat.  It wasn't too complicated but at the same time had a nice level of challenge to it that gave you a sense your own skill matttered.  The kill moves were also pretty good (with the possible exception of one where you slit the throat of a skeleton which just seemed silly, but I can live with that when the rest was pretty cool).  There are also a LOT of cut scenes, the developers devoted a lot of time to this and they're generally pretty good.  It gives the game a more cinematic feel which was fun.Okay so that's the good, now for the bad.Not everything is explained very well, so I found myself sometimes just saving, trying things and reloading until I had a sense of what I should do or what was the best decision because the game didn't give me enough info about various skills and so forth to make anything other than a random guess.  Couple of examples.  Spending glory on skills and attributes, I was never entirely sure how important different ones, what the effect of raising one attribute vs another really was or how useful some skills were.  Another example, whether to keep or sell some things I'd gathered.  I gathered a LOT of iron ore, gold ore, etc. but by the end of the game all the gold ore was still sitting in my inventory.  Should I have sold it, was there some crafting I could have done with it but missed, or was it just another form of ""wealth"", I don't know and the game never explained this.  This was my first Risen game experience so perhaps previous games had explained this but, again I don't know.  But for someone coming to the game franchise for the first time some parts of the game were a bit too puzzling.  Overall though these problems didn't stop me from enjoying the game.  Also the game doesn't prevent you from saving at any time you like and you can have as many saves as you wish so you can always just save, experiment with choices and then reload as necessary.There's a lot of weapon choices but your armor / clothing choices were limited so being able customize your character's appearance was likewise limited more than that I would have liked.  (I guess Skyrim has me really spoiled with all the options I got used to there.)   If you have the Adventurer's Garb, which I did, I wore it for much of the game.One other criticism I would have is that once you finish the main story line the game ends, there's no option to continue in a sandbox mode as you can with other games such as Skyrim.  There is a lot to explore and with such an engaging main story line its easy to miss stuff.  But I don't necessarily want to start a new game or go back to one of my many older save points just to finish exploring a richly detailed game world.  So the lack of a sandbox mode after finishing the main story line would have been a plus in my book.Lastly, if the game developers happen to read this I have a small criticism about the game ending.  I don't want to give away any spoilers here so I'm going to be a bit vague.  But, the end cut scene was abrupt and short.  Your hero emerges you briefly see your friends and then it cuts to you sailing away and rolls credits.  As it cuts from seeing your friends to sailing away, that was very abrupt and for a game that had so many well done cut scenes the ending felt a bit anti-climatic and short.  So just wanted to point that out, it could have done with more of a celebration and renunion with your friends and crew at the end after such a big final battle.Overall though I'd very much recommend the game.  All the important aspects of the game worked, nothing felt broken to me or unfinished.  I had a lot of fun exploring the world the game presents, getting to know the NPCs, forming alliances and making enemies.  Some of the sarcastic dialog was just FUN, it was nice to play a game where you really could tell an NPC, ""Hey, you know you're a moron, right?""  LOL"
