76561198011982884,Not Recommended,249230,16694898,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Carlos77,"Even though I'm a huge Pyranha Bytes fanboy and I can forgive them a lot....I just can't recommend this game. Gothic 1, Gothic 2, Gothic 3 and Risen 1 are all absolutely amazing games and I recommend wholeheartedly every one of them. I can even recommend Risen 2 even though it's nowhere near as good as the previous games. But Risen 3 is just too a blatant attempt to extract some more money from the Risen 2 engine and assets without too much effort.This game still retains some of PB's trademark systems and there IS some enjoyment to be found if you look hard enough. On the other hand it just exudes an uninterested, glassy, dreary atmosphere. The story is a complete joke, the writing lacks the spark and wit of Risen 2, NPCs are vapid and long winded, quests are boring, character models and entire areas are cynically rehashed and reused and the combat, the greatest strength of PB games, isn't very satisfying either. There's way too much of it and it stops being challenging or interesting very quickly, especially if you go for the mage build. You're just blasting hordes of trash mobs again and again into oblivion. Sometimes it feels like a 3rd person Diablo which is the complete opposite of what PB games traditionaly strived for.Many fans claimed Risen 2 marked the end of true Pyranha Bytes but Risen 2, even though a significant decline, is still worth playing. Risen 3 is not. It's cynical, disinterested, boring and routine rehash of Risen 2, nothing more."
,Not Recommended,249230,26092450,"Posted: 17 October, 2016",all,Drakevarg,"I wanted to like this. Risen 3 is clearly a bigger, more ambitious, and more polished product than its predecessors, which always felt like they wanted to be bigger than they were. The combat is slightly less clunky than before, but still recognizably the traditional Piranha Bytes plodding, stunlock-loving style that I would inevitably toggle God Mode to avoid eventually.The fact that I can't actually do that this time without 3rd party programs is a factor in my negative review.Honestly, the killer problem with this game, the one bad enough to make it the first of these games since Gothic for me to abandon outright a few hours in, is that it's just horribly balanced. I don't mean ""unfair"" - Piranha Bytes games are always unfair. But normally they're a consistant level of unfair that simply presents a steep learning curve, like a poor man's Dark Souls.Risen 3, meanwhile, is just plain inconsistent. You can be playing along, managing to more-or-less stay on top and not meeting the traditional fate of being stunlocked to death by a passing ostrich, when you'll wander into an unremarkable-sounding quest and be killed in three shots by some complete nobody that the game in no way warns you is fully capable of handing you your♥♥♥♥♥on a platter. And with no way to cheat my way around it this time around so I can enjoy the parts of the game that aren't awful, I simply don't have the patience to roll the dice every single time I fight a new enemy and hope that they just haven't arbitrarily decided to make this nondescript monster deal five times as much damage as everyone around him.I suppose it's worth noting that this inconsistency is foreshadowed somewhat by the story, which is by far the least concrete of the series. After a kind of rushed-feeling tutorial level, you're thrown into the wide open world with what the previous games would've called late first-act gear and a vague mission to do something about your missing spirit. I didn't like the way Risen 2 bottlenecked you for the first third/half of the game by locking you onto a single story path, but at least it gave me time to understand what the hell I was doing and what the stakes were. Risen 3 by comparison legitimately feels like the entire first act is just missing, and I frequently find myself feeling like I'm showing up to certain areas prematurely as random plot points are discussed as if I should have been told about them beforehand somewhere else.Between that and the random difficulty curve, I'm not sure the game was designed to be as open-ended as it is, and ultimately it just winds up feeling like a mess. I know it's not Piranha Bytes' style, but this is probably one game that could have benefitted from the traditional RPG approach of having character and quest levels to guide the player along. The intent was to make a game that doesn't hold the player's hand, and I can applaud that, but I don't have the patience with a game that not only doesn't tell me what to do, but then kicks me in the gut whenever I fail to read its mind about what it expects me to do. ""Open-ended challenge"" isn't the same thing as ""be psychic or die."""
