76561198015387033,Recommended,249230,31045827,Posted: 9 April,all,Paaaaatrick,"Having just finished Risen 3, thought this would be a good moment to put down my thoughts..I have been a longtime fan of Piranha Bytes.  From their earliest releases such as Gothic & Gothic 2, to their jump over to the Risen series, I have always found their games to be enjoyable, but always needing more polish.  Risen 3 is no exception to this.I stopped and started the game several times before I really sat down and played through it.  And, in the end, I'm glad I did.  It felt very much like putting back on a good pair of shoes again, just comfortable to be able to play the game, and in the end I pushed through it quickly because I wanted to get to the end.  Much like the last 2 games in the series, the ending was a little disappointing, but I did enjoy the experience of getting there.There are bugs, there are wonky issues with inventory and resolution and other items.  But, look up a few FAQs and whatnot and you can get past most of it.  From a programming side of things, the game was.. competent.  It always feels like they need just a few more months, or just some extra money, and they could pull off what would be considered to be a AAA game.I would recommend this to others, and while it is nice to have the previous experience of Risen 1 and 2, it isn't entirely necessary to have played those to enjoy this one."
76561197993903913,Not Recommended,249230,14327139,"Posted: 4 February, 2015",all,OneOfMany,"Why? Why Piranha Bytes, why must you hurt me like this?It's like you've taken the good parts of their older games and thrown them all out, while at best not doing anything about the bad parts, and at worst magnifying them, or even shoehorning new ones from other games in.The NPC Hubs, unlike the ones from about every Gothic game they made, seem empty and dead. The liveliest one is the Guardians big hold, but it's a single one, compared to the countless other ones that simply seem...barren. The inter NPC banter which made the towns in Gothic and Risen seem especially lively is almost completely missing, as is the ambiance that came with it. Most of the NPCs become completely meaningless, after you've done a sweep through their area and finished whatever quest they were involved in. Unlike the previous games, there are almost no quests that become available at a later point, making the gameworld seem even more devoid of life. Because apparently nothing happens while you're away.Choosing a faction also has almost no impact. There is only a handfull of faction-dependant perks, most of which carry little weight. Apart from that, faction dictates which set of spells becomes permanently available to you, but during one playthrough I found a sufficient amount of scrolls to make that meaningless as well. After that, the only thing left are AFAIK about 2 quests per faction that wouldn't be available without joining. There are almost no other reactions or consequences to your choice in faction. Though that might be rooted in the choice to have no conflict between the factions, which I think is a rather boring design choice.Along with the factions comes the comparable tiny variety of equipment. There is a miniscule selection of 3 sets of armor per faction and they don't have that much impact on gameplay, as the values of armor seem laughable (150 points of damage mitigation, of which about 115 are from character attributes and perks at the end of my playthrough).  Though there are a bit more weapons available, a good part of those are already useless at the point one can optain them.All special abilities and perks no longer cost any learning points. All that is left is an amount of gold one has to pay for them, which undoubtably enables players to get anything they want without any need for choice. And with the Potion Brewing Perk, which costs 2000 gold pieces, the upper half of the attribute scale becomes meaningless as well. Why invest experience points into enhancing an attribute past a value of 50, if one can instead do it with not that hard to get potions?The Sea-Battle minigame they implemented seems like a sloppy attempt of copying Assassins Creed's sea battles, but with only 3 instances happening, none of which are avoidable, I couldn't familiarize with it's mechanics enough to be particularily good. It thus simply became a chore, each one taking about 20 minutes of gametime, while not being any kind of fun or adding anything to the story. The other three minigames were less of a chore, but also weren't required at any point, which is a good thing I guess. Why the hell they decided to implement the seabattles, and do so the way they did still is beyond me.The other, more ""puzzely"" possiblities of the game were mostly ignored. The ""trained monkey"" sequences were few in number and rarely provided anything of value (only 2 times IIRC). Same goes with the ""transform into Parrot"" sequences. There was only a hand full of them, and most of them only provided mediocre loot. None of them were in any part needed for any quests, neither main nor side. In fact, there weren't even meaningful possiblities to use them during the mainquest.The final battle was (again) only a ""whack the damage sponge"" with the occasional ""follow the damage sponge"" which felt kinda anti-climatic.While you get seven possible followers, it's of little meaning which one of them you take with you. They simply didn't add that much, appart from distracting monsters during combat and only occasional lines of banter. The game simply never made me (as a player) care that much about them. Of the three followers that I never took along, there is one whom I never found out anything but his name and his fondness of Alcohol, one I only found out that he had gotten ret-conned into a cruel, mercyless ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, and one that only seemed to be fond of stealing things. Nothing else. Nothing upon which I could build any feelings towards these characters but disinterest.So I have to ask: What the hell went wrong at Piranha Bytes? Why did you build something so completely forgettable, so unbelievably mediocre, so underwhelmingly plain? You guys were the heroes of my youth. A small scale studio, making such incredibly awesome games. And now this... please Piranha Bytes, please stop slacking.Edit1: ""PC Gamer: 83%""...guess thats where the money that would've improved chapters 3 and 4 went."
