76561198295864780,Not Recommended,249230,24138813,"Posted: 6 July, 2016",all,SouthwardGolf7,"My negative rating is based purely on my own opinion, so will differ from that of others.I think conceptually, the game has a lot going for it; the levels are nice, it is graphically pleasing, the characters (despite the very VERY poor voice acting) are unique and interesting, and the pirate setting is fun - but that's all.The voice acting is very tedious. I'm not one to get hung up on such details, but when a game relies so heavily on conversing with NPC's, it can/has ruin/ed a/this game.The story is so diffuse I struggled to know what was going on, and i'm very much a narrative junkie. Where to to go, why you're going there, and what to do next were questions that for me were left unanswered. Don't get me wrong, I enjoy running about 'just because', but after the story is done.I struggled through these ~4 hours of gameplay, and, unfortunately, didn't enjoy much of it. I have Risen 2 and 1, so I will give those a go. The game holds promise, but falls flat. For those looking for a fun RPG, look elsewhere. For those who have exhausted all possible RPG's, go play a FPS."
,Not Recommended,249230,16713697,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Radnen,"Full disclosure: I'm coming at this review from an action-rpg perspective, such as The Witcher III, Skyrim and Kingdoms of Amalur.I've heard people say they like this game and even some people have defended the game's combat, but I can't seem to understand them when there are a plethora of games that have better-feeling combat systems. This review will be a breakdown of the combat system in this game. Bear in mind, I am playing the Witcher III, and yes I am comparing this to a game like that because I need a benchmark for what a good battle systemfeelslike. Because that's the thing I'm not hearing often enough about this game... that the combat system may be likable but itfeelsfar off the mark.So, what I dislike out of the gate is the fact I have to unlearn all the best systems in the past. There are no real parry moves, blocking or dodging of any kind. Sure you can roll, but it's really hampered. In other games like Amalur and Witcher III, a roll is a dodge that puts you in a better position to combo. In this game it's more of a get-out-of-the-way move that ends up being a chore for how often you do it, and you can never align it correctly. Sure you can roll out to a better position for comboing and sure if you've gotten used to this system, you may even say it's just as good, but you have to realize you are getting used to afloaty and unrealistic fighting system. I'm just now getting the hang of it and I'm fighting the opponents in different ways than I prefer. It feels really cheap oftentimes to attack in certain ways in this game. The Witcher III seems to have a graceful sliding system with the dodge mechanic that can be used to great effect if timed correctly. But I find the timing in this game to be rather hard to figure out.The next gripe I have is with the attacks. They feel very floaty and I cannot feel for where the tip of the sword is, this small concept is proving to be a huge nuisance. Games like Skyrim or The Witcher III have very decent positional relation with the blade. I can tell easily if an opponent is within range. Even more off putting, the character ice-skates to his opponent in the game, which is harder yet to control. Also I've noticed that while in mid ""ice-skate"" the enemy can still attack you from the front. Which is odd since I'm coming right at it. Games like Amalur which does have a kind of skating system, at least feel satisfying for connecting with the opponent in rewarding ways.The attacks also seem slow and the combos don't stack. If I hit the attack button and quickly move to 'parry' or block, it seems to cancel the move which is not what I'm used to. I was half hoping the attack continues and the character moves into a parry stance, much like other games with really nice animation. This subtly makes the fighting feelunnuanced and robotic.There are patterns to most enemies you encounter, but they don't have a rhyme or reason. It's quite random how you handle even the most basic encounters. Rolling and attacking, waiting for them to do two attacks so you can get them with one attack. Waiting for them to charge an attack, etc. It also doesn't help that your attacks at first don't seem to deal much damage. Basic encounters can be long winded if you focus too much on blocking and rolling and not dealing enough damage.Groups are hard to manage. The best solution is to attack randomly until they die off evenly, or getting lucky enough to isolate one of them. But in other games there are usually ways to cope with groups. In the Witcher for example, the character can parry and attack and dodge enemies coming in from the sides or behind and what's better is you can do that by timing it in that game. In this game, the character isacrobatically feable, which makes it rather hard to do any impressive sword swashbuckling. If it isn't one of two states you can be in, you'tre screwed. Even Assassins Creed games get this right. It also helps if enemies all don't attack at once but circle you until they are ready to leap. I know you might think that system is cheap, but it certainly goes a long ways in creating a believable action game where the hero has to fight multiple enemies. But it mainly comes down to flank-parry recognization: The idea you can turn an opponents attack around when they arrive from the side.Finally, where are the skills? I haven't gotten far enough along to unlock shield-breaking moves, different combos, stun moves, etc. I was hoping to have some experience of this before the first trainers, but the game really hampers you in the beginning and that leaves a rather dull first impression. I find it hard to keep coming back to this game because of it.That's my experience with it. So if you prefer really nice action games, please steer away from this or you'll be cursing about how bad this system is before you get any good at it. It definitely is not a system I picked up and liked immediately like Witcher III or other similar, better combat games."
